<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="607" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[173,659,1123,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,300,1602,1623]" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Busanello and Caron" authorityYear="2016" box="[312,527,1601,1623]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Microlinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="607" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perobanus">
<emphasis box="[312,527,1601,1623]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">Microlinus perobanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName box="[173,258,1628,1650]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Microlinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="607" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pusio">
<emphasis box="[173,193,1628,1650]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[206,258,1628,1650]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">pusio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having the head and abdomen darker than the rest of the body, the labrum truncate on the anterior margin, and the apex of the median lobe of the aedeagus clearly tapered and pointed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="610" pageId="2" pageNumber="607" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[706,1194,194,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[731,922,194,215]" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">Description. Male.</emphasis>
Maximum body length 
<quantity box="[706,787,221,242]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="2" pageNumber="607" unit="mm" value="2.5">2.5 mm</quantity>
, maximum elytral width 
<quantity box="[1046,1127,221,242]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="607" unit="mm" value="0.4">0.4 mm</quantity>
. Body elongate and parallel-sided (
<figureCitation box="[976,1033,247,268]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[197,228,1026,1045]" captionTargetBox="[173,659,194,1003]" captionTargetId="figure-614@2.[173,659,194,1003]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Microlinus perobanus, holotype. Scale bar =" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5339659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5339659/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); brownish with head and abdomen darker and appendices lighter. Body glossy; head with minute, sparse setigerous punctation, gradually disappearing towards midline; pronotum with dorsal and lateral rows of setigerous punctures; elytral and abdominal setigerous punctation fine, sparse, gradually disappearing towards midline on abdomen. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[933,993,433,454]" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">Head:</emphasis>
Longer than wide, slightly widened posteriorly; eyes small and not prominent, tempora longer than length of eyes. Antenna distinctly geniculate and short (
<figureCitation box="[1117,1181,513,534]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[175,214,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[151,1171,186,1639]" captionTargetId="figure-0@3.[151,1171,186,1639]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–9. Microlinus perobanus, male. 2) Antenna; 3) Labrum, dorsal view; 4) Mandibles, dorsal view; 5) Maxilla, dorsal view; 6) Labium, ventral view; 7) Protibia and protarsus, external view; 8) Tergite VIII, dorsal view; 9) Sternite VIII, ventral view. Scale bars = 2) 0.5 mm; 3) 0.125 mm; 4–9) 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5339661" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5339661/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
); antennomeres III–XI with dense, fine pubescence; scape and pedicel longer than wide, scape longest, almost as long as 5 following antennomeres combined; antennomeres III–X conspicuously wider than long, gradually increasing in width towards apex; antennomere XI longer than wide, almost as long as 2 preceding antennomeres combined. Labrum short, slightly transverse (
<figureCitation box="[1039,1099,725,746]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[175,214,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[151,1171,186,1639]" captionTargetId="figure-0@3.[151,1171,186,1639]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–9. Microlinus perobanus, male. 2) Antenna; 3) Labrum, dorsal view; 4) Mandibles, dorsal view; 5) Maxilla, dorsal view; 6) Labium, ventral view; 7) Protibia and protarsus, external view; 8) Tergite VIII, dorsal view; 9) Sternite VIII, ventral view. Scale bars = 2) 0.5 mm; 3) 0.125 mm; 4–9) 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5339661" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5339661/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
); anterior margin truncate; lateral angles sinuous; long apical setae. Mandibles almost symmetric, with 2 internal teeth (
<figureCitation box="[765,824,805,826]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[175,214,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[151,1171,186,1639]" captionTargetId="figure-0@3.[151,1171,186,1639]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–9. Microlinus perobanus, male. 2) Antenna; 3) Labrum, dorsal view; 4) Mandibles, dorsal view; 5) Maxilla, dorsal view; 6) Labium, ventral view; 7) Protibia and protarsus, external view; 8) Tergite VIII, dorsal view; 9) Sternite VIII, ventral view. Scale bars = 2) 0.5 mm; 3) 0.125 mm; 4–9) 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5339661" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5339661/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Maxilla with galea extending beyond apex of lacinia (
<figureCitation box="[856,913,832,853]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[175,214,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[151,1171,186,1639]" captionTargetId="figure-0@3.[151,1171,186,1639]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–9. Microlinus perobanus, male. 2) Antenna; 3) Labrum, dorsal view; 4) Mandibles, dorsal view; 5) Maxilla, dorsal view; 6) Labium, ventral view; 7) Protibia and protarsus, external view; 8) Tergite VIII, dorsal view; 9) Sternite VIII, ventral view. Scale bars = 2) 0.5 mm; 3) 0.125 mm; 4–9) 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5339661" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5339661/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
); palpomere I as long as wide and shortest; palpomere II as long as wide, conspicuously widened at apex; palpomere III 2 times wider than long, slightly narrowing toward apex; palpomere IV thin and about half length of palpomere III. Labium with palpomere II longer than III, widest at median third (
<figureCitation box="[1016,1075,991,1012]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[175,214,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[151,1171,186,1639]" captionTargetId="figure-0@3.[151,1171,186,1639]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–9. Microlinus perobanus, male. 2) Antenna; 3) Labrum, dorsal view; 4) Mandibles, dorsal view; 5) Maxilla, dorsal view; 6) Labium, ventral view; 7) Protibia and protarsus, external view; 8) Tergite VIII, dorsal view; 9) Sternite VIII, ventral view. Scale bars = 2) 0.5 mm; 3) 0.125 mm; 4–9) 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5339661" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5339661/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
); palpomere III thin, parallel-sided. Gular sutures fused at basal half. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[763,845,1044,1065]" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">Thorax:</emphasis>
Pronotum 1.5 times longer than wide; apical fourth with sides converging to anterior margin and basal 3/4 somewhat parallel-sided; anterior margin emarginated. Prosternum slightly elevated medially, with a short, triangular process. Elytra slightly longer and wider than pronotum; metathoracic wings developed; mesocoxae separated from each other by distance about half width of each mesocoxa, mesoventrite process broad and somewhat pointed at the apex. Tarsal formula 5-5-5; protibia with internal emargination on apical third (
<figureCitation box="[774,841,1336,1357]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[175,214,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[151,1171,186,1639]" captionTargetId="figure-0@3.[151,1171,186,1639]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–9. Microlinus perobanus, male. 2) Antenna; 3) Labrum, dorsal view; 4) Mandibles, dorsal view; 5) Maxilla, dorsal view; 6) Labium, ventral view; 7) Protibia and protarsus, external view; 8) Tergite VIII, dorsal view; 9) Sternite VIII, ventral view. Scale bars = 2) 0.5 mm; 3) 0.125 mm; 4–9) 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5339661" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5339661/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
, black seta); protarsus with first 4 tarsomeres strongly dilated (
<figureCitation box="[986,1042,1363,1384]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[175,214,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[151,1171,186,1639]" captionTargetId="figure-0@3.[151,1171,186,1639]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–9. Microlinus perobanus, male. 2) Antenna; 3) Labrum, dorsal view; 4) Mandibles, dorsal view; 5) Maxilla, dorsal view; 6) Labium, ventral view; 7) Protibia and protarsus, external view; 8) Tergite VIII, dorsal view; 9) Sternite VIII, ventral view. Scale bars = 2) 0.5 mm; 3) 0.125 mm; 4–9) 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5339661" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5339661/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
); metatibia with apical ctenidium. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[895,1001,1390,1411]" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">Abdomen:</emphasis>
Segments III–VII parallel-sided; tergite VIII with posterior margin slightly projected on median third (
<figureCitation box="[1045,1103,1443,1464]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[175,214,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[151,1171,186,1639]" captionTargetId="figure-0@3.[151,1171,186,1639]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–9. Microlinus perobanus, male. 2) Antenna; 3) Labrum, dorsal view; 4) Mandibles, dorsal view; 5) Maxilla, dorsal view; 6) Labium, ventral view; 7) Protibia and protarsus, external view; 8) Tergite VIII, dorsal view; 9) Sternite VIII, ventral view. Scale bars = 2) 0.5 mm; 3) 0.125 mm; 4–9) 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5339661" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5339661/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
); sternite VIII with posterior margin rounded (
<figureCitation box="[1056,1114,1469,1490]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[175,214,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[151,1171,186,1639]" captionTargetId="figure-0@3.[151,1171,186,1639]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 2–9. Microlinus perobanus, male. 2) Antenna; 3) Labrum, dorsal view; 4) Mandibles, dorsal view; 5) Maxilla, dorsal view; 6) Labium, ventral view; 7) Protibia and protarsus, external view; 8) Tergite VIII, dorsal view; 9) Sternite VIII, ventral view. Scale bars = 2) 0.5 mm; 3) 0.125 mm; 4–9) 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5339661" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5339661/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
); tergite IX without ventral struts (
<figureCitation box="[982,1060,1496,1517]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="4.[197,236,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[214,1154,183,1643]" captionTargetId="figure-0@4.[214,1154,183,1643]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 10–15. Microlinus perobanus. 10) Male tergites IX and X, dorsal view; 11) Male sternite IX, ventral view; 12) Aedeagus, ventral view; 13) Female tergite VIII, dorsal view; 14) Female tergites IX and X, dorsal view, anterior margin of tergite X with dashed line; 15) Female sternite IX, ventral view. All scale bars = 0.25 mm, except 12) 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5339663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5339663/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
); sternite IX 2 times longer than wide, base rounded, apex barely sclerotized with set of setae somewhat resembling a crown (
<figureCitation box="[778,847,1576,1597]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="4.[197,236,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[214,1154,183,1643]" captionTargetId="figure-0@4.[214,1154,183,1643]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 10–15. Microlinus perobanus. 10) Male tergites IX and X, dorsal view; 11) Male sternite IX, ventral view; 12) Aedeagus, ventral view; 13) Female tergite VIII, dorsal view; 14) Female tergites IX and X, dorsal view, anterior margin of tergite X with dashed line; 15) Female sternite IX, ventral view. All scale bars = 0.25 mm, except 12) 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5339663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5339663/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
); tergite X 2 times longer than wide, apex barely sclerotized with set of setae somewhat resembling a crown (
<figureCitation box="[914,986,1629,1650]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="4.[197,236,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[214,1154,183,1643]" captionTargetId="figure-0@4.[214,1154,183,1643]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 10–15. Microlinus perobanus. 10) Male tergites IX and X, dorsal view; 11) Male sternite IX, ventral view; 12) Aedeagus, ventral view; 13) Female tergite VIII, dorsal view; 14) Female tergites IX and X, dorsal view, anterior margin of tergite X with dashed line; 15) Female sternite IX, ventral view. All scale bars = 0.25 mm, except 12) 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5339663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5339663/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
). Aedeagus elongate, median lobe almost 3 times longer than parameres (
<figureCitation box="[713,784,1682,1703]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="4.[197,236,1662,1681]" captionTargetBox="[214,1154,183,1643]" captionTargetId="figure-0@4.[214,1154,183,1643]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 10–15. Microlinus perobanus. 10) Male tergites IX and X, dorsal view; 11) Male sternite IX, ventral view; 12) Aedeagus, ventral view; 13) Female tergite VIII, dorsal view; 14) Female tergites IX and X, dorsal view, anterior margin of tergite X with dashed line; 15) Female sternite IX, ventral view. All scale bars = 0.25 mm, except 12) 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5339663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5339663/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="607">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
); median lobe tapered and pointed at apex, lateral lobes slightly exceeding apex of median lobe.
</paragraph>
